thread.title: WA to get 65 per cent of royalties from Woodside-run LNG project
thread.title_full: WA to get 65 per cent of royalties from Woodside-run LNG project

title: WA to get 65 per cent of royalties from Woodside-run LNG project
text:
THE Federal Government has signed an agreement to give almost two thirds of the royalties of a Woodside-run gas project to Western Australia.
The Torosa petroleum pool, which is expected to be developed through the proposed Browse floating LNG project, sits on both Commonwealth and Western Australian lease areas off the Kimberley coast.
Industry Minister Ian Macfarlane signed an agreement with the WA government on Wednesday which will allocate 65.4 per cent of the royalties to the state.
Around 34 per cent will go to the Commonwealth.
The deal came about after the discovery of the so-called “golden rocks” in 2014.
In 2014, the discovery of three rocks off the Kimberley coast means WA’s share of Woodside’s Browse gas field jumped from about five per cent to 65 per cent.
The rocky outcrops were technically islands and formed part of the North Scott Reef, which prompted a redrawing of WA’s maritime boundaries.
Before the discovery, almost the entire area was in Commonwealth waters and the petroleum royalties would have flowed to Canberra.
Woodside is yet to make a final investment decision on the project and Mr Macfarlane acknowledged there was still “much work” to be done before the project was viable.
Originally published as WA gets royalty boost from LNG project
